<br>
Also, I believe that there is evidence of tropical forests such as the Amazon being around for tens of thousands of years (they are too close to the equator to be glaciated) - a crust role recent enough to be &quot;remembered&quot; by the Egyptians (I'm assuming an absolute max of about 20 or 30 thousand years here) should curtail the age of these ecosystems to less than their known age.<br>
<br>
The above comments about the asteroid theory I proposed are also good - even if a &quot;normal&quot; dust cloud wasn't kicked up, some characteristic materials should have been produced from the collision which would show up in ice cores and would probably have been noticed.  So the theory can probably be proven to not hold up.  Might still be worth making another study of the ice cores, though... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=captainbeowulf>CaptainBeowulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/21/03 6:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Polar Shifts</span><hr size=1> Just to add to my comments above - I decided to take a look at the links posted (which I should have done before I posted myself) and the suggestion of *some* polar shift seems plausible - it also seems possible that fast shifts could do a lot of damage.  Polar shifts that retain the poles roughly in the extreme northerly and southerly latitudes of the hemisphere, along with the equator remaining roughly around the major tropical forests like the Amazon, could be consistent with the extant evidence.  The version of this theory that I was criticizing above was that which I've seen more frequently - that Antarctica was on the equator etc.  A more plausible pole-shift theory could, however, tie in with what we know of climate change and the ice ages. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=marki